
Fields of the XAACursorInfo structure:

Flags

    This is a set of flags that defines a number configuration parameters
    of hardware cursor.

    USE_HARDWARE_CURSOR

    Indicates whether to use the generic hardware cursor interface at
    all.

    HARDWARE_CURSOR_TRUECOLOR_AT_8BPP

    Indicates that at 8bpp, the background and foreground pixel values
    passed in SetCursorColors will be in 8-8-8 truecolor format, as
    opposed to an 8-bit palette index.

    HARDWARE_CURSOR_PROGRAMMED_BITS

    Indicates that a special function (LoadCursorImage) is provided to
    upload the cursor image to the card. This is useful if the cursor
    image must be uploaded with programmed I/O, or when the video memory
    format required is not supported by XAA.

    HARDWARE_CURSOR_BIT_ORDER_MSBFIRST

    Indicates that the bit order within each byte of cursor bitmap data
    must be reversed.

    HARDWARE_CURSOR_PROGRAMMED_ORIGIN

    Indicates that there is support for a programmed origin into the
    cursor bitmap in the SetCursorPosition function. This is useful
    when the cursor is partially visible at the left or top of the
    screen. If this is not defined, "skewed" cursor bitmap data must
    be transferred explicitly in this kind of situation. XAA currently
    does not do this automatically.

    HARDWARE_CURSOR_AND_SOURCE_WITH_MASK

    Indicates that the source data must be ANDed with the mask data to
    arrive at cursor bitmap data compatible with the chip. This is
    required when the hardware cursor data is in Windows format.

    HARDWARE_CURSOR_SWAP_SOURCE_AND_MASK

    Indicates that the source and mask data bytes must be swapped. Some
    cirrus chips need this flag in combination with the one above.

    HARDWARE_CURSOR_SOURCE_MASK_INTERLEAVE

    For the HARDWARE_CURSOR_CHAR_BIT_FORMAT we interleave the mask and
    the source bit by bit so that ABCDEFGH and 12345678 (represent a byte
    for the mask then source) becomes H8G7F6E5 D4C3B2A1.

    HARDWARE_CURSOR_LONG_BIT_FORMAT
    HARDWARE_CURSOR_SHORT_BIT_FORMAT
    HARDWARE_CURSOR_CHAR_BIT_FORMAT

    Indicates that each source/mask written is either a char, short or
    long. Most chipsets here will be char, which then does not need to
    be specified.

MaxWidth
MaxHeight

    The maximum supported hardware cursor width and height, which must
    be a multiple of 8.

CursorDataX
CursorDataY

    The video memory location where the cursor data must be stored
    (only relevant if PROGRAMMED_BITS is not set).

SetCursorColors(bg, fg)

    This function must set the background (mask) and foreground colors
    of the cursor. The color values passed are in 8-8-8 RGB format
    (blue byte first), except at 8bpp, provided that the
    TRUECOLOR_AT_8BPP flag is not set.

SetCursorPosition(x, y, xorigin, yorigin)

    This function must set the hardware cursor position to (x, y). The
    optional xorigin and yorigin paramaters, when the
    PROGRAMMABLE_ORIGIN flag set, define the offset into the cursor
    bitmap (which is used when the cursor is partially visible at the
    top or left sides of the screen).

LoadCursorImage(bits, xorigin, yorigin)

    This function must be defined if PROGRAMMABLE_BITS is set. It
    should upload the cursor bitmap data to the card (using programmed
    I/O, or to video memory if the format is not supported). The cursor
    bitmap data is stored with mask and source bytes interleaved; each
    mask is followed by a source byte. However, the data is affected
    the optional flags indicating MSB-first bit order, and swapping and
    ANDing of the source and mask data. The size corresponds to the
    maximum supported size.

HideCursor()

    This function must disable the hardware cursor (make it invisible).

ShowCursor()

    This function must make the hardware cursor visible again.
    Some chipsets have the option of using a Windows or X11 based cursor.
    Enabling of the appropriate one should be done here too.



